---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Design a Web Crawler — Interactive Visualization"
  description="Understand web crawler architecture: BFS/DFS traversal, URL frontier, politeness policies, bloom filters, distributed crawling. Interactive simulation."
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: "Home", href: "/" },
    { label: "System Design", href: "/system-design/" },
    { label: "Web Crawler", href: "/system-design/web-crawler/" }
  ]}
>
  <div class="viz-container">
    <header class="viz-header">
      <h1>&#x1F577;&#xFE0F; Design a Web Crawler</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Explore crawling algorithms, URL frontiers, politeness policies, and distributed architecture</p>
    </header>

    <section class="overview-section">
      <div class="overview-card">
        <p>
          A <strong>web crawler</strong> (or spider) systematically browses the web to index content. It starts from
          <strong>seed URLs</strong>, fetches pages, extracts links, and adds them to a <strong>URL frontier</strong> for
          future crawling. Key challenges include <strong>politeness</strong> (not overloading servers),
          <strong>deduplication</strong> (avoiding re-crawling), <strong>prioritization</strong> (crawling important pages first),
          and <strong>scale</strong> (billions of pages across millions of domains). Explore each component below.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- SECTION 1: BFS/DFS Crawl Visualization                      -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <section class="crawl-section">
      <h2>&#x1F310; BFS vs DFS Crawl Traversal</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">Watch how a crawler discovers pages using Breadth-First Search (explore all links on a page before going deeper) vs Depth-First Search (follow links as deep as possible first). Toggle the strategy and observe the traversal order.</p>

      <div class="crawl-controls">
        <div class="control-group">
          <label>Seed URL:</label>
          <input type="text" id="seedUrlInput" value="example.com" class="text-input" />
        </div>
        <div class="control-group">
          <label>Strategy:</label>
          <div class="pattern-buttons">
            <button class="pattern-btn active" data-strategy="bfs" id="bfsBtn">&#x1F4CA; BFS</button>
            <button class="pattern-btn" data-strategy="dfs" id="dfsBtn">&#x1F4C9; DFS</button>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="control-group">
          <label>Speed:</label>
          <input type="range" id="crawlSpeed" min="1" max="10" value="5" />
          <span id="speedLabel">5</span>
        </div>
        <div class="control-group">
          <button id="startCrawlBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">&#x25B6;&#xFE0F; Start Crawl</button>
          <button id="resetCrawlBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">&#x1F504; Reset</button>
          <button id="stepCrawlBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn-secondary">&#x23ED;&#xFE0F; Step</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="crawl-viz-wrapper">
        <div class="graph-panel">
          <h3>Web Graph</h3>
          <canvas id="graphCanvas" width="700" height="450"></canvas>
          <div class="legend">
            <span class="legend-item"><span class="dot unvisited"></span> Unvisited</span>
            <span class="legend-item"><span class="dot frontier-dot"></span> In Frontier</span>
            <span class="legend-item"><span class="dot crawling"></span> Crawling</span>
            <span class="legend-item"><span class="dot visited"></span> Visited</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="frontier-panel">
          <h3 id="frontierTitle">&#x1F4E5; URL Frontier (Queue - BFS)</h3>
          <div class="frontier-list" id="frontierList"></div>
          <div class="crawl-log">
            <h4>&#x1F4DD; Crawl Log</h4>
            <div class="log-entries" id="crawlLog"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="crawl-stats">
            <div class="stat"><span class="stat-l">Visited</span><span class="stat-v green" id="visitedCount">0</span></div>
            <div class="stat"><span class="stat-l">In Frontier</span><span class="stat-v yellow" id="frontierCount">0</span></div>
            <div class="stat"><span class="stat-l">Total Found</span><span class="stat-v blue" id="totalFound">0</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- SECTION 2: URL Frontier & Priority Queue                     -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <section class="frontier-section">
      <h2>&#x1F4CB; URL Frontier &amp; Priority Queue</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">The URL frontier is the data structure that stores URLs to be crawled. It uses a <strong>front queue</strong> (priority-based) feeding into <strong>back queues</strong> (one per domain for politeness). URLs are prioritized by PageRank, freshness, or domain importance.</p>

      <div class="frontier-controls">
        <div class="control-group">
          <label>Add URL:</label>
          <input type="text" id="newUrlInput" value="https://news.example.com/article" class="text-input wide" />
        </div>
        <div class="control-group">
          <label>Priority:</label>
          <select id="prioritySelect" class="select-input">
            <option value="high">High (PageRank &gt; 0.8)</option>
            <option value="medium" selected>Medium (PageRank 0.4-0.8)</option>
            <option value="low">Low (PageRank &lt; 0.4)</option>
          </select>
        </div>
        <div class="control-group">
          <button id="enqueueBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">&#x2795; Enqueue</button>
          <button id="dequeueBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn-secondary">&#x2796; Dequeue Next</button>
          <button id="autoFrontierBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">&#x25B6;&#xFE0F; Auto Demo</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="frontier-viz-wrapper">
        <div class="front-queues-panel">
          <h3>&#x1F3AF; Front Queues (Priority)</h3>
          <div class="priority-queues">
            <div class="pq-lane" id="pqHigh">
              <div class="pq-label high">HIGH</div>
              <div class="pq-items" id="pqHighItems"></div>
            </div>
            <div class="pq-lane" id="pqMedium">
              <div class="pq-label medium">MEDIUM</div>
              <div class="pq-items" id="pqMediumItems"></div>
            </div>
            <div class="pq-lane" id="pqLow">
              <div class="pq-label low">LOW</div>
              <div class="pq-items" id="pqLowItems"></div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="arrow-col">&#x27A1;&#xFE0F;</div>
        <div class="back-queues-panel">
          <h3>&#x1F3E0; Back Queues (Per-Domain Politeness)</h3>
          <div class="domain-queues" id="domainQueues"></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="frontier-metrics">
        <div class="stat"><span class="stat-l">Total Enqueued</span><span class="stat-v green" id="totalEnqueued">0</span></div>
        <div class="stat"><span class="stat-l">Total Dequeued</span><span class="stat-v yellow" id="totalDequeued">0</span></div>
        <div class="stat"><span class="stat-l">Domains</span><span class="stat-v blue" id="domainCount">0</span></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- SECTION 3: Politeness & robots.txt                           -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <section class="politeness-section">
      <h2>&#x1F916; Politeness &amp; robots.txt</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">Well-behaved crawlers respect <code>robots.txt</code> directives and enforce crawl delays to avoid overwhelming servers. This simulator shows how URLs are filtered and delayed.</p>

      <div class="politeness-wrapper">
        <div class="robots-panel">
          <h3>&#x1F4C4; robots.txt</h3>
          <pre class="robots-file" id="robotsFile">User-agent: *
Crawl-delay: 2
Disallow: /admin/
Disallow: /private/
Disallow: /api/internal/
Allow: /api/public/

User-agent: MyBot
Crawl-delay: 1
Disallow: /secret/
Allow: /</pre>
          <div class="robots-controls">
            <label>User-Agent:</label>
            <select id="userAgentSelect" class="select-input">
              <option value="generic">GenericBot (*)</option>
              <option value="mybot">MyBot</option>
            </select>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="filter-panel">
          <h3>&#x1F50D; URL Filter Test</h3>
          <div class="url-test-list" id="urlTestList"></div>
          <div class="control-group" style="margin-top:12px;">
            <input type="text" id="testUrlInput" value="/admin/settings" class="text-input wide" />
            <button id="testUrlBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">&#x1F50E; Test URL</button>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="delay-panel">
          <h3>&#x23F1;&#xFE0F; Crawl Delay Timeline</h3>
          <div class="timeline-viz" id="timelineViz"></div>
          <button id="startTimelineBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn-secondary">&#x25B6;&#xFE0F; Simulate Crawl Delay</button>
          <div class="delay-info" id="delayInfo">
            <span>Crawl-delay: <strong id="currentDelay">2</strong>s between requests to the same host</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- SECTION 4: Bloom Filter for Deduplication                    -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <section class="bloom-section">
      <h2>&#x1F3AF; Bloom Filter for URL Deduplication</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">A Bloom filter is a space-efficient probabilistic data structure used to test whether a URL has already been seen. It may produce <strong>false positives</strong> (says "seen" when not) but <strong>never false negatives</strong>.</p>

      <div class="bloom-controls">
        <div class="control-group">
          <label>URL to check:</label>
          <input type="text" id="bloomUrlInput" value="https://example.com/page1" class="text-input wide" />
        </div>
        <div class="control-group">
          <button id="bloomAddBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">&#x2795; Add URL</button>
          <button id="bloomCheckBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn-secondary">&#x1F50E; Check URL</button>
          <button id="bloomResetBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">&#x1F504; Reset</button>
          <button id="bloomDemoBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn-secondary">&#x25B6;&#xFE0F; Auto Demo</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bloom-viz-wrapper">
        <div class="bloom-array-panel">
          <h3>Bit Array (<span id="bloomSize">64</span> bits)</h3>
          <div class="bit-array" id="bitArray"></div>
          <div class="bloom-hash-info" id="bloomHashInfo">Add a URL to see which bits get set</div>
        </div>

        <div class="bloom-results-panel">
          <h3>&#x1F4CA; Results</h3>
          <div class="bloom-log" id="bloomLog"></div>
          <div class="bloom-stats">
            <div class="stat"><span class="stat-l">URLs Added</span><span class="stat-v green" id="bloomAdded">0</span></div>
            <div class="stat"><span class="stat-l">Bits Set</span><span class="stat-v yellow" id="bitsSet">0</span></div>
            <div class="stat"><span class="stat-l">Fill Ratio</span><span class="stat-v blue" id="fillRatio">0%</span></div>
            <div class="stat"><span class="stat-l">False Positives</span><span class="stat-v red" id="falsePositives">0</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="bloom-comparison">
        <h3>&#x1F4BE; Space Comparison</h3>
        <div class="comparison-bars">
          <div class="comp-row">
            <span class="comp-label">Bloom Filter (64 bits)</span>
            <div class="comp-bar-track"><div class="comp-bar bloom-bar" id="bloomSpaceBar" style="width:8%"></div></div>
            <span class="comp-value" id="bloomSpaceVal">8 bytes</span>
          </div>
          <div class="comp-row">
            <span class="comp-label">HashSet (avg 40 bytes/URL)</span>
            <div class="comp-bar-track"><div class="comp-bar hashset-bar" id="hashsetSpaceBar" style="width:0%"></div></div>
            <span class="comp-value" id="hashsetSpaceVal">0 bytes</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- SECTION 5: Distributed Crawling Architecture                 -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <section class="distributed-section">
      <h2>&#x1F30D; Distributed Crawling Architecture</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">At scale, a single machine cannot crawl the entire web. Multiple crawler workers coordinate through a central URL frontier, using consistent hashing to assign domains to workers.</p>

      <div class="dist-controls">
        <div class="control-group">
          <label>Workers:</label>
          <input type="range" id="workerCount" min="2" max="8" value="4" />
          <span id="workerLabel">4</span>
        </div>
        <div class="control-group">
          <button id="startDistBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn">&#x25B6;&#xFE0F; Start Distributed Crawl</button>
          <button id="resetDistBtn" class="action-btn reset-btn">&#x1F504; Reset</button>
          <button id="addDomainBtn" class="action-btn primary-btn-secondary">&#x2795; Add Domain</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="dist-viz-wrapper">
        <div class="coordinator-panel">
          <div class="coordinator-box">
            <h3>&#x1F3AF; Coordinator</h3>
            <div class="coord-info">URL Frontier &amp; Domain Assigner</div>
            <div class="coord-queue" id="coordQueue"></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="hash-ring-panel">
          <h3>Consistent Hash Ring</h3>
          <canvas id="hashRingCanvas" width="300" height="300"></canvas>
        </div>

        <div class="workers-panel">
          <h3>Crawler Workers</h3>
          <div class="workers-grid" id="workersGrid"></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="dist-stats">
        <div class="stat"><span class="stat-l">Active Workers</span><span class="stat-v green" id="activeWorkers">4</span></div>
        <div class="stat"><span class="stat-l">URLs/sec</span><span class="stat-v yellow" id="crawlRate">0</span></div>
        <div class="stat"><span class="stat-l">Domains Assigned</span><span class="stat-v blue" id="domainsAssigned">0</span></div>
        <div class="stat"><span class="stat-l">Total Crawled</span><span class="stat-v green" id="totalCrawled">0</span></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- SECTION 6: Architecture Deep Dive                            -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <section class="architecture-section">
      <h2>&#x1F3D7;&#xFE0F; Architecture Deep Dive</h2>

      <div class="arch-grid">
        <div class="arch-card">
          <h3>&#x1F310; DNS Resolver &amp; Caching</h3>
          <p>Crawlers make millions of DNS lookups. A local DNS cache avoids redundant queries. Strategies include:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Local DNS cache</strong> with TTL-based expiry</li>
            <li><strong>Pre-fetching</strong> DNS for domains in the frontier</li>
            <li><strong>Dedicated DNS resolver</strong> to avoid OS resolver bottlenecks</li>
            <li>Cache hit rates of 90%+ reduce latency dramatically</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="arch-diagram">
            <div class="arch-flow">
              <span class="arch-node">URL</span>
              <span class="arch-arrow">&#x2192;</span>
              <span class="arch-node highlight">DNS Cache</span>
              <span class="arch-arrow">&#x2192;</span>
              <span class="arch-node">IP Address</span>
              <span class="arch-arrow">&#x2192;</span>
              <span class="arch-node">HTTP Fetch</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="arch-card">
          <h3>&#x1F4C4; Content Parsing &amp; Extraction</h3>
          <p>After fetching a page, the crawler parses HTML to extract links and content:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Link extraction</strong> from &lt;a&gt;, &lt;link&gt;, &lt;script&gt;, &lt;img&gt; tags</li>
            <li><strong>URL normalization</strong> (remove fragments, resolve relative URLs)</li>
            <li><strong>Content type detection</strong> (HTML, PDF, images, etc.)</li>
            <li><strong>Language detection</strong> for multi-lingual crawling</li>
            <li><strong>JavaScript rendering</strong> for SPAs (expensive, selective)</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="arch-diagram">
            <div class="arch-flow">
              <span class="arch-node">Raw HTML</span>
              <span class="arch-arrow">&#x2192;</span>
              <span class="arch-node highlight">Parser</span>
              <span class="arch-arrow">&#x2192;</span>
              <span class="arch-node">Links + Text</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="arch-card">
          <h3>&#x1F504; Duplicate Detection</h3>
          <p>Beyond URL dedup, content-level dedup avoids storing identical pages served from different URLs:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>URL fingerprinting</strong> with Bloom filters (seen above)</li>
            <li><strong>Content hashing</strong> (MD5/SHA-256 of page body)</li>
            <li><strong>SimHash / MinHash</strong> for near-duplicate detection</li>
            <li><strong>URL canonicalization</strong> (trailing slashes, www, http/https)</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="arch-diagram">
            <div class="arch-flow">
              <span class="arch-node">Page Content</span>
              <span class="arch-arrow">&#x2192;</span>
              <span class="arch-node highlight">SimHash</span>
              <span class="arch-arrow">&#x2192;</span>
              <span class="arch-node">Fingerprint DB</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="arch-card">
          <h3>&#x1F4BE; Storage Layer</h3>
          <p>Crawled data must be stored efficiently for indexing and analysis:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>WARC files</strong> (Web ARChive format) for raw page storage</li>
            <li><strong>Object storage</strong> (S3) for page content blobs</li>
            <li><strong>Metadata DB</strong> (crawl time, status, headers) in distributed KV store</li>
            <li><strong>Inverted index</strong> for full-text search (downstream)</li>
            <li><strong>Compression</strong> (gzip, zstd) for 3-5x space savings</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="arch-diagram">
            <div class="arch-flow">
              <span class="arch-node">Fetched Page</span>
              <span class="arch-arrow">&#x2192;</span>
              <span class="arch-node highlight">Storage</span>
              <span class="arch-arrow">&#x2192;</span>
              <span class="arch-node">WARC + S3 + DB</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="arch-card">
          <h3>&#x1F4CA; Monitoring &amp; Metrics</h3>
          <p>A production crawler needs comprehensive observability:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Pages/sec</strong> per worker and globally</li>
            <li><strong>Error rates</strong> (timeouts, 4xx, 5xx, DNS failures)</li>
            <li><strong>Frontier size</strong> and drain rate</li>
            <li><strong>Domain distribution</strong> to detect hot spots</li>
            <li><strong>Content freshness</strong> metrics for re-crawl scheduling</li>
            <li><strong>Resource utilization</strong> (CPU, memory, bandwidth, disk I/O)</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="arch-diagram">
            <div class="arch-flow">
              <span class="arch-node">Workers</span>
              <span class="arch-arrow">&#x2192;</span>
              <span class="arch-node highlight">Metrics Pipeline</span>
              <span class="arch-arrow">&#x2192;</span>
              <span class="arch-node">Dashboard</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="arch-card">
          <h3>&#x1F680; Scaling Strategies</h3>
          <p>Scaling from thousands to billions of pages requires:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Horizontal scaling</strong> — add more crawler workers</li>
            <li><strong>Domain partitioning</strong> — consistent hashing across workers</li>
            <li><strong>Geographic distribution</strong> — crawl from regions near target servers</li>
            <li><strong>Adaptive crawl rates</strong> — based on server response times</li>
            <li><strong>Incremental re-crawling</strong> — prioritize changed pages via sitemaps, HTTP 304</li>
            <li><strong>Tiered storage</strong> — hot (SSD), warm (HDD), cold (archive)</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="arch-diagram">
            <div class="arch-flow">
              <span class="arch-node">1 Worker</span>
              <span class="arch-arrow">&#x2192;</span>
              <span class="arch-node highlight">Shard</span>
              <span class="arch-arrow">&#x2192;</span>
              <span class="arch-node">N Workers</span>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <!-- SECTION 7: Key Design Decisions                              -->
    <!-- ============================================================ -->
    <section class="decisions-section">
      <h2>&#x2696;&#xFE0F; Key Design Decisions</h2>
      <p class="section-desc">Every web crawler design involves critical tradeoffs. Click each card to explore the reasoning behind the choices.</p>

      <div class="decision-grid">
        <div class="decision-card" data-decision="traversal">
          <div class="decision-header">
            <h3>&#x1F500; Breadth-First vs Depth-First</h3>
            <span class="decision-toggle">&#x25BC;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-body">
            <div class="tradeoff-row">
              <div class="tradeoff-side pro">
                <h4>BFS (Preferred)</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li>Discovers diverse domains quickly</li>
                  <li>Better for building a broad index</li>
                  <li>Natural priority ordering by link depth</li>
                  <li>Avoids spider traps (infinite depth)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="tradeoff-side con">
                <h4>DFS</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li>Lower memory usage (no large queue)</li>
                  <li>Good for deep-crawling single sites</li>
                  <li>Can get stuck in spider traps</li>
                  <li>Poor diversity across domains</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="verdict">&#x2705; Most production crawlers use <strong>BFS with priority</strong> — combines breadth with importance-based ordering.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="decision-card" data-decision="freshness">
          <div class="decision-header">
            <h3>&#x1F504; Freshness vs Completeness</h3>
            <span class="decision-toggle">&#x25BC;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-body">
            <div class="tradeoff-row">
              <div class="tradeoff-side pro">
                <h4>Freshness Focus</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li>Re-crawl popular pages frequently</li>
                  <li>Use sitemaps &amp; change frequency hints</li>
                  <li>Prioritize dynamic content</li>
                  <li>Higher bandwidth usage</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="tradeoff-side con">
                <h4>Completeness Focus</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li>Crawl as many unique pages as possible</li>
                  <li>Long-tail pages get attention</li>
                  <li>Risk of stale content for popular pages</li>
                  <li>Better for archival / research</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="verdict">&#x2705; Balance both: use <strong>adaptive re-crawl intervals</strong> based on observed change rates. High-change pages re-crawled more often.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="decision-card" data-decision="politeness">
          <div class="decision-header">
            <h3>&#x1F3CE;&#xFE0F; Politeness vs Speed</h3>
            <span class="decision-toggle">&#x25BC;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-body">
            <div class="tradeoff-row">
              <div class="tradeoff-side pro">
                <h4>Polite Crawling</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li>Respect robots.txt &amp; crawl-delay</li>
                  <li>Max 1 request per domain per second</li>
                  <li>Good reputation, avoid IP bans</li>
                  <li>Slower overall throughput per domain</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="tradeoff-side con">
                <h4>Aggressive Crawling</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li>Higher throughput per domain</li>
                  <li>Faster discovery of all pages</li>
                  <li>Risk of getting blocked / IP banned</li>
                  <li>Can degrade target server performance</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="verdict">&#x2705; Always be polite. Parallelize across <strong>many domains simultaneously</strong> to maintain high global throughput while being gentle per domain.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="decision-card" data-decision="storage">
          <div class="decision-header">
            <h3>&#x1F4BE; Store Raw HTML vs Parsed Content</h3>
            <span class="decision-toggle">&#x25BC;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-body">
            <div class="tradeoff-row">
              <div class="tradeoff-side pro">
                <h4>Store Raw HTML</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li>Can re-parse with improved algorithms</li>
                  <li>Full fidelity for archival</li>
                  <li>Much more storage needed</li>
                  <li>Standard WARC format compatibility</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="tradeoff-side con">
                <h4>Store Parsed Only</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li>Smaller storage footprint</li>
                  <li>Faster downstream processing</li>
                  <li>Cannot re-extract if parser improves</li>
                  <li>Lossy transformation</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="verdict">&#x2705; Store <strong>both</strong>: raw HTML in cold storage (S3/archive) and parsed content in hot storage for processing. Compression makes raw storage affordable.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="decision-card" data-decision="dedup">
          <div class="decision-header">
            <h3>&#x1F3AF; Bloom Filter vs HashSet for Dedup</h3>
            <span class="decision-toggle">&#x25BC;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-body">
            <div class="tradeoff-row">
              <div class="tradeoff-side pro">
                <h4>Bloom Filter</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li>O(1) lookup, extremely space-efficient</li>
                  <li>~1 byte per URL at 1% false positive rate</li>
                  <li>Cannot enumerate or delete entries</li>
                  <li>False positives mean some URLs skipped</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="tradeoff-side con">
                <h4>HashSet</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li>Exact membership test (no false positives)</li>
                  <li>~40-100 bytes per URL (full string stored)</li>
                  <li>Can enumerate and delete entries</li>
                  <li>Does not scale to billions of URLs in memory</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="verdict">&#x2705; Use a <strong>Bloom filter for in-memory fast checks</strong> backed by a persistent set (RocksDB/LevelDB) for exact verification when needed.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="decision-card" data-decision="render">
          <div class="decision-header">
            <h3>&#x1F4F1; Render JavaScript or Not</h3>
            <span class="decision-toggle">&#x25BC;</span>
          </div>
          <div class="decision-body">
            <div class="tradeoff-row">
              <div class="tradeoff-side pro">
                <h4>Render JS (Headless Browser)</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li>See content loaded dynamically (SPAs)</li>
                  <li>More accurate link discovery</li>
                  <li>10-100x more expensive per page</li>
                  <li>Complex infrastructure (Chrome pool)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="tradeoff-side con">
                <h4>Static HTML Only</h4>
                <ul>
                  <li>Fast and lightweight</li>
                  <li>Simple infrastructure</li>
                  <li>Misses JS-rendered content</li>
                  <li>Good enough for most pages</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="verdict">&#x2705; Two-tier approach: <strong>static crawl first</strong>, then selectively render important/JS-heavy domains with a headless browser pool.</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

  </div>
</BaseLayout>

